          "body": "The remnant's response to Jeremiah's commitment (42:4) is a solemn self-imprecatory oath: 'May the LORD be a true and faithful witness against us if we do not act in accordance with the whole message with which the LORD your God will send you to us' (42:5). This is legally significant. They are not merely promising to obey; they are calling YHWH as the legal witness who will testify against them if they fail. Verse 6 makes the commitment absolute: 'Whether it is pleasant or unpleasant, we will listen to the voice of the LORD our God.' The phrasing 'whether pleasant or unpleasant' is remarkable — they are explicitly pre-committing to obey even a word that contradicts their desire. This is precisely the word that will come, and precisely the word they will refuse. The oath becomes, by chapter's end, a self-pronounced indictment. Jeremiah does not need to condemn them — they have condemned themselves with their own words (cf. Matthew 12:37). The theological weight here is sobering: invoking God as witness is not a protection against disobedience; it only sharpens the charge when disobedience follows."
