        "number": 2,
        "title": "Ten days of silence and the word that came",
        "range": "42:7-9",
        "excerpt": "Now at the end of ten days the word of the LORD came to Jeremiah.",
        "body": "The ten-day interval is one of the most pastorally significant silences in the prophetic literature. Jeremiah does not produce an answer the day the question is asked. He waits — and in the context of the chapter's later exposure of the remnant's self-deception, the wait is a mercy that was not used. Ten days in which the commanders and the people could have examined the real intention of their hearts, could have tested whether their oath was genuine, could have begun to orient themselves toward obedience before the answer arrived. The text gives no indication that they did any of this; by 42:20-21, Jeremiah's language implies the decision for Egypt was essentially settled throughout.\n\nThe formula 'thus says the LORD the God of Israel, to whom you sent me to present your petition before Him' (42:9) is architecturally significant. Jeremiah anchors the oracle in the remnant's own initiative — they sent him, they commissioned the inquiry, they established the terms of the engagement in their oath. He is not bringing an unsolicited word; he is returning with the answer to the question they asked. This makes the subsequent disobedience more culpable, not less: the word comes through the channel they opened, from the God they invoked, via the prophet they sent. Every element of the delivery mechanism was of their own construction.\n\nThe divine self-identification — 'the God of Israel' (elohei yisrael, 42:9) — is politically pointed. The remnant is contemplating flight to Egypt, to a foreign sovereign's territory. YHWH identifies Himself not as the God of the cosmos in abstract but as the covenant God of Israel — the God of this people, this land, this specific history. His claim on them is not generic but covenantally particular. The answer to their question comes from within the covenant relationship they have been trying to exit.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qets eser yamim* (at the end of ten days, v.7) — *qets* means end, limit, the appointed termination point; the ten days are a bounded period of divine deliberation, not an indefinite wait. *Naphal techinnah* (present your petition, v.9) — literally 'cause the petition to fall before His face'; the idiom of prostrating a request before a superior."
